<Layout title="Reflections — Yash Shah">

<h1>Optik Consultancy Reflection</h1>
  <!-- Repeat this block once for each Task 1a question -->

  <section>
    <h2>What were your expectations about your internship before you joined?</h2>
    <p>Before the internship, I expected to be assigned a low-skill project designed to cater to my lack
of experience in a professional software environment. I also anticipated that I might not enjoy
the experience, as the 9-to-5 commitment seemed questionable when many software roles
offer hybrid or remote flexibility. Furthermore, I assumed that supervisors would constantly
monitor my actions and that I would not be trusted with larger-scale, high-impact projects.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>What was the reality? How was it different from your expectations?</h2>
    <p>The internship was far more challenging and rewarding than I had anticipated. While I quickly
adapted to the 9-to-5 schedule, the work itself was much more substantial: I was tasked with
building a fully functional product with my team within a 12-week timeframe. Despite having
never handled a full-stack project of this scale, I was grateful for the opportunity to deliver a
complete product. Most surprisingly, I was given significant autonomy, as my supervisors and
team leads trusted me to manage my own workload and meet deadlines independently.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>What lessons were the most important from your internship. Why were they important?</h2>
    <p>One of the most critical lessons was the significance of effective daily standups. While I had
used them sparingly in university, seeing them integrated with project management tools like
Jira and Trello in a professional setting showed me how they prevent tasks from being delayed
without the team's knowledge. Additionally, I learned the importance of team accountability. By
holding each other responsible for our specific tasks and actions, we were able to maintain
momentum and successfully develop a functioning product as a cohesive unit.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
    <h2>After your workplace experience, what would you say your value proposition would be to an
employer? How can you demonstrate this?</h2>
    <p>My core value proposition is adaptability. I entered this internship with no prior experience in
full-stack development or AI-RAG pipelines. Although the initial weeks were difficult as I learned
to navigate client meetings and technical updates, I rapidly adjusted. I can demonstrate this
adaptability through my record of opening and reviewing multiple pull requests, integrating
client feedback regarding my professional manner, and receiving positive stakeholder reviews
on the final code base.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>How did your internship influence the type of role in which you are interested?</h2>
        <p>The internship sparked a strong interest in AI development, specifically in prompt engineering
and model enhancement. However, noticing that I did not have the opportunity to work directly
on APIs or databases during this tenure, I have identified a new career goal: transitioning into
Backend Development to master the architectural side of software. Furthermore, I am now
interested in DevOps roles, as I am eager to learn the technicalities of how complex
applications and websites are deployed and maintained in production.</p>
    </section>
